The Old Restart Policy :


[Service]
Restart=always
RestartSec=5s
StartLimitBurst=5
StartLimitIntervalSec=60

______________________________________


The New Restart Policy For PHP-FPM : 


[Service]

Restart=always
RestartSec=5s

StartLimitIntervalSec=120
StartLimitBurst=10
StartLimitAction=none

MemoryMax=1.5G
OOMPolicy=restart

KillSignal=SIGQUIT

WatchdogSec=30s

CPUQuota=80%


---------------------------------------------

Now let's see this new restart policy Benefit's and Behaviour/!!!\


My old Restart policy only covers :

Simple restart on crash
Risk of restart loops
No memory control


But this new Restart policy covers:

- Controlled restart recovery
- No infinite crash loops
- Auto recovery from OOM kill
- Memory-safe execution
- System-level health monitoring
- Production stability under load spikes


Now let's see each parameter explanation : 
------------------------------------------

* Restart=always

This means : If PHP-FPM stops for any reason, systemd brings it back automatically.



* RestartSec=5s 

This parameters means : Adds a small delay before restart to avoid repeated crash loops



* StartLimitIntervalSec=120

Simple explanation: Detects repeated crashes quickly and Helps to control unstable service behaviour



* StartLimitBurst=10

means: this parameter only Allows max 10 restart attempts in that interval. This will Prevents infinite restart loop, and also Protects CPU from overload.


* StartLimitAction=none 

Benefit of adding this parameter: 
Even if it crashes too much, system won’t permanently shut it down, it Still allows manual recovery...


* MemoryMax=1.5G

Importance of this parameter: 

PHP-FPM cannot use more than 1.5GB RAM. alos this one Limits PHP-FPM memory usage so it cannot crash the server....


* OOMPolicy=restart

Benefit of this parameter: 

If Linux kills PHP-FPM due to memory (OOM killer), systemd restarts it automatically, there's no Auto recovery after memory crash, No manual intervention needed... this parameter will take care.... 


* KillSignal=SIGQUIT

benefit : This parameter Gives PHP-FPM time to finish active requests before stopping....


* WatchdogSec=30s

benefit of adding this parameter : 

If PHP-FPM hangs or becomes unresponsive, system detects it and restarts it!! even this will Detects frozen PHP-FPM and Auto-restarts if stuck.


* CPUQuota=80%

benefit : Stops PHP-FPM from consuming full CPU and affecting other services, also this can Prevents CPU spikes and Protects NGINX / DB / OS...!!!




